398. cedo. In conversation a query is often put logically but not grammatically dependent on another verb or sentence, eg. on such expletives as dic mihi, uide, cedo, &e So often in Plautus and Terence when later writers would make the query dependent and use the subjunctive. Cf. our ‘ Tell me, where are you? ’ Roby, ἓξ 1761, 1605, 1607. [-do, future imperative; pl. cette=eedite found only in early scenio poets.]
